7. USER INTERFACE DESIGN
7.1 UI Design Principles
1. Consistency All pages share consistent layout, navigation, and visual styling. Header, navigation menu, and button styles remain the same across all screens to ensure familiar experience.
2. Simplicity Pages are stripped down to remove visual clutter. Users can easily see how to accomplish their goals without unnecessary elements.
3. Minimize User Effort All activities can be initiated within three clicks:
•	One click from home to any major function
•	Maximum three clicks total for complex workflows (e.g., Home → Review Requests → Select specific request)
4. Error Prevention
•	School names selected from dropdown (not typed)
•	Dates selected from calendar picker
•	Times selected from time picker
•	Required fields enforced before submission
•	Clear error messages guide users to missing information
7.2 Screen Inventory
The prototype will implement 8 screens:
1.	Home - Role-based navigation hub
2.	Submit Request - Reservation request form
3.	Pending Requests - List of requests awaiting review
4.	Review Request - Detail view for request review
5.	Quote Creation - Quote generation form (Operations Staff only)
6.	Calendar View - Event calendar with filters
7.	Reference Documents - Document library
8.	Archived Requests - Historical request access
Note: The prototype will fully implement screens 1-4 and 6 (Home, Submit Request, Pending Requests, Review Request, Calendar View). Screens 5, 7, and 8 may be represented with placeholder buttons.
